Perspectives for Sino-American Relations in 2019
NEW YORK – In 2018, the new and increasingly unpredictable dynamics of China-U.S. relations unsettled much of Asia.
One year ago, U.S. President Donald Trump returned from his particularly grand "state visit plus" to Beijing, which China had hoped would finally put Trump's anti-China campaign rhetoric behind him.
Twelve months later, China and the United States are entangled in a trade war, and the Trump government has replaced the U.S. "strategic engagement" with China with "strategic competition."
Moreover, one year ago, the U.S., European, and Chinese economies and markets were booming.
Today, there is great uncertainty in financial markets, growth is slowing in China and Europe, and in America, higher interest rates are beginning to take effect.
The uncertainty regarding the future development of nuclear negotiations with North Korea also clouds the picture.
What, then, are the prospects for U.S.-China relations in 2019?
It is likely that an agreement on reducing the bilateral trade deficit and on the import decisions China will make in this regard will be reached by March.
An agreement on lowering tariffs is also possible by then, although the complexity of the issue could extend the targeted timeframe.
If tariffs were negotiated one by one, it could take a year.
If Chinese economic reformers, however, were to adopt a more drastic approach, gradually committing themselves over time to the abolition of all tariffs and asking Americans to do the same, a faster result could be achieved.
This would, however, run counter to Chinese trade officials who have been trained for decades to be stingy, let alone give everything up at once.
The reform of so-called forced technology transfer should be relatively straightforward.
Nevertheless, reform is one thing, and the way contractual agreements might be implemented in practice is another, even if there were no specific provisions regarding technology transfer.
The protection of intellectual property is, however, extremely problematic.
Previous agreements made under the government of President Barack Obama could be reaffirmed.
However, enforcing them or taking legal action against violations of intellectual property rights remains a hopeless endeavor.
A possible mechanism would be to subject relevant contracts between Chinese and foreign companies to international commercial arbitration institutions based in Singapore or Switzerland, which are specifically tasked with enforcing the protection of intellectual property.
Should China object, it could develop its own international commercial arbitration system based in China.
To do so, however, it would have to appoint qualified foreigners to its arbitration panel in order to strengthen its international credibility.
No one has trust in Chinese commercial courts.
For its own domestic reform needs, China must move toward completely independent commercial and civil chambers within its judicial system, even though the criminal chamber continues to be subject to political control.
American concerns regarding state subsidies under the country's "Made in China 2025" strategy will be difficult to resolve.
The fact is that all countries provide a certain degree of state support to their domestic technology sectors, although this is highest in China.
Even if we were to prescribe a maximum level of state support for a particular company, compliance would be difficult to assess.
I am not confident that a negotiation outcome will be achieved in this area.
Perhaps America must simply outcompete China by increasing public investments in research and development in the fields of information technology and biotechnology.
We should also not rule out the possibility that China might offer tariff reforms to the rest of the international community.
Thus, China could gradually decide to take the drastic step of agreeing to tariff-free trade not only with the USA, but with all member states of the World Trade Organization.
In this way, China would have an almost irresistible opportunity to position itself as a champion of global free trade and to stand up to the trend of protectionism.
In the course of such a shift, China could request membership in the Trans-Pacific Partnership (TPP) from its member states, in order to surpass the United States (which withdrew from the free trade agreement as one of Trump's first official actions) in the Asia-Pacific region.
China can be remarkably agile when it discovers a political opening and market access.
The negotiations would be difficult, but Japan's reservations about China's accession to the TPP have decreased since the recent visit of Prime Minister Shinzo Abe to Beijing.
Given the central strategic challenges in its relationship with the United States, China is likely to seek to reduce conflicts in its relations with other countries in its general foreign and security policy in 2019.
In relations with Japan, there is already a certain normalization.
Recent data from the Japanese Coast Guard indicate a significant reduction in Chinese incursions into the area of the Senkaku/Diaoyu Islands in the East China Sea.
China also wants to ease tensions with the Association of Southeast Asian Nations over the South China Sea by accelerating negotiations on a "code of conduct."
Moreover, China is likely to have a more relaxed relationship with India following the bilateral summit in Wuhan in April.
And China could begin to moderate its stance toward Taiwan, given the electoral defeat suffered by the Democratic Progressive Party, which supports independence, led by Taiwanese President Tsai Ing-wen, in the local and regional elections last month.
This would of course change radically if the USA continues with further significant arms sales to Taiwan, which is likely.
Incidents at sea with the USA in the South China Sea continue to occur, and the conflict could escalate if the USA more forcefully reaffirms its stance on "freedom of navigation" next year.
Across all of Eurasia, China will continue to implement its major project, the "New Silk Road."
In recent months, however, the initiative has caused less political hype in China.
Among Chinese officials, there are already discussions about revising certain modalities, following Sri Lanka's handover of the Hambantota port to China, which triggered negative reactions and raised concerns regarding the long-term financiability of the New Silk Road.
2019 could therefore see fewer triumphant news reports about the New Silk Road.
Furthermore, China is likely to consolidate and expand its role within the United Nations and existing Bretton Woods institutions, rather than highlighting new institutions of international political action.
It will probably continue to appear as a new advocate of the WHO and maintain its stance on global climate change, as agreed in the 2015 Paris Climate Agreement.
More prudent representatives of China's foreign policy establishment believe it is better to focus on existing mechanisms of the global rules-based system, especially if the USA consistently shows contempt for them.
While China tries to stabilize its relations with the USA and reduce tensions in its relations with other countries, its leadership will probably use the year 2019 to form a well-founded judgment about the future of US policy: The consequences of the Mueller investigation for Trump and his government, and whether a new president in 2020 (or earlier) would change the new US strategy in any way.
Although they have already concluded that America's stance toward China has changed profoundly, they are still uncertain what exact form this change takes and whether it represents a fundamental shift in strategy (as opposed to tactical measures).
